I"ì<p>I‚Äôll share my thoughts about more cores in a CPU after my recent searching for a photographer laptop for my sister.</p>

<p>Limit of maximum frequency
Advancements of CPU frequency has slowed down severely due to known physics limitations. It‚Äôs the main reason why performance improvements are made by adding more cores to CPUs. Quite easily done when power consumption is not an issue.</p>

<p>On laptops the performance efficiency is crucial. To keep the same TDP (an indicator for a CPU power consumption [W]) producers needed to find some savings.</p>

<p>Cost of higher performance</p>

<p>Power = Frequency * Voltage</p>

<p>but higher frequency requires higher voltages. Look at the chart how much higher voltages are used on desktops.
On mobile, the more linear part of the curve is used. The consequence is lower max. frequency (even more limited when more cores are on load) which gives the savings.</p>

<p>Let‚Äôs compare the processing of an easily parallelizable task between one core at 4Ghz and 4 cores at 1Ghz. In both scenarios, we have effective 4Ghz.
In both cases, processing will be finished at the same time but with different efficiency. 4 cores are set to a much lower voltage so you have power savings.</p>

<p>Unfortunately, many tasks aren‚Äôt well scalable to be used on multi-cores efficiently. That‚Äôs why single-core performance is the most important for scoring ‚Äúproductivity‚Äù capabilities of a CPU.</p>

<p>Where are the gains?
Lets compare 9gen 4core cpu vs. a 6core one. Both has TDP limit of 45W.</p>

<p>single-thread performance is higher due to a bit higher clocks
  without power limits 50% more cores would give 50% gains on 8-thread test
  efficiency per wat is almost identical in both CPUs.</p>

<p>Conclusions</p>

<p>the higher TDP (lower power limits) the more gains from more cores,
  CPUs from U series which have 15W TDP gains are the lowest.
  For productivity, gains are marginal. Think twice before you‚Äôll pay more for more cores in a CPU.</p>

<p>Exceptions
There two additional effects to achieve higher clocks for more expensive CPUs:</p>

<p>Better wafer area. A wafer is the source of the mase material of CPU in a circular form. The closer to the centre the better statistically the material is. Better material means a bit better efficiency.
  Marketing. The material quality difference is far too little to make consumers buying more expensive CPUs. Showing same TDP and higher clocks suggestions that you pay more for something better.</p>

